content:
I have a small repository called lazy-scripts.
At first, it was exactly what the name says: a bunch of lazy scripts. Nothing fancy. Some helpers to clean my Python environment, create a simple sandbox folder to make tests, and automate things I repeat too much in my daily developer life.
But after some time, this repository became something different for me. It became the place where I started to understand how I can really use AI as a developer, not only as a chat where I ask questions and copy code.
The first idea was very practical.
I wanted commands that save me small amounts of time:
create a disposable development sandbox;
clean generated files from projects;
copy some reusable GitHub Actions workflows;
make repetitive local tasks easier.
This is still the base of the repository. I do not see it as a professional CLI product. It is more like my personal toolbox.
Today the repository has commands like:
bouli-sandbox, to recreate a local sandbox and open it in VS Code;
dev-garbage-collector, to clean Python, JavaScript, and Go generated files;
dev-lazy-gh, to copy reusable GitHub Actions workflows;
ai-sbx-codex, to start Codex inside an sbx sandbox;
ai-sbx-opencode, to start OpenCode inside an sbx sandbox;
ai-ralph-codex, to run my Ralph workflow with Codex.
The interesting part is that the repository history shows my own learning path. It started with simple shell scripts, and slowly became a place to test AI workflows with more control.
Like many developers, I started using AI in the most obvious way.
I was creating code in a chat, copying it, downloading files, testing locally, asking again, fixing again.
It worked, but it was not a real workflow. It was more like using a very advanced autocomplete outside of my project.
